Shares in Brait, a South African investment heavyweight in which tycoon Christo Wiese owns about a third of its stock, slumped 6% on Wednesday in what one fund manager said was a knock-on effect from a sell-off in Steinhoff. Wiese is the top shareholder in Steinhoff, which dropped nearly 70% after revealing accounting irregularities and its CEO quit, shocking investors and tarnishing Wiese’s image as one of South Africa’s most respected stewards of shareholder capital.     Read: Steinhoff shares plunge after CEO Markus Jooste quits Read: The extent of Steinhoff’s value destruction Read: Steinhoff shareholder wants to see ‘huge effort’ to publish results